Sometimes too the force of thei-*blow itself strikes out fire, when the force of wind discharged in a cold state with· out fire has struck, because sure enough, when it has smitten with a powerful stroke, the elements of heat are able to stream together out of the wind itself and at the same time out of the thing which then en- counters the stroke. Thus, when we strike a stone with iron, fire ffies out 3 and none the less, because the force of the iron is cold, do its seeds of fiery brightness meet together upon the stroke. Therefore in the same way a thing ought to be set on fire by the thunderbolt, if it has hap- pened to be in a state suited to receive and susceptible of the flames. At the same time the might of the wind cannot lightly be thought to be absolutely and decidedly cold, seeing that it is discharged with such force from above 3 but if it is not already set on fire during its course, it yet arrives in a warm state with heat mixed up in it.
